    "body": "**Godot version:**\r\n3.0, 3.1\r\n\r\n**Issue description:**\r\nThis is a feature request.  Currently, as far as I can tell, the only way to get/set the bitmask flags for an autotile in a tileset is to manually address them by their path in the resource using get()/set().  This is a bit obscure since it's not documented and there's a possibility that compatibility breaks between versions.  \r\n\r\nFor people who wish to use the autotiling features by generating their own atlas at runtime, it would be helpful to expose the bitmask flags to the user, identifying by name or index in the tileset as an argument if it is a function, or as a key specified to a property.  The return type can be the raw array as it exists currently, but perhaps a more straightforward return type would be a Dictionary of <Vector2, int>.\r\n\r\nSome possible syntaxes:\r\n```gdscript\r\nvar tileset = Tileset.new()\r\nvar id = 0\r\ntileset.create_tile(id)\r\n#[add code to set texture and other basic boilerplate here]\r\n\r\nvar pos = Vector2(x,y)  #Might be more ideal to have separate x,y for nested loop, but...\r\n\r\n#Func syntax\r\ntilset.get_bitmask_flags(id)   #Returns entire data structure, or Dict:<Vector2,Int>\r\ntilset.get_bitmask_flag(id, pos.x, pos.y)  #Returns int\r\ntilset.set_bitmask_flags(id)   #Requires data structure in native format\r\ntilset.set_bitmask_flag(id, pos, value)  #Returns some kind of error enum\r\n\r\n#Property syntax\r\ntileset.bitmask_flags[id]  #Returns entire data structure, but as Dict:<Vector2, Int>\r\ntileset.bitmask_flags[id][pos]   #Returns int\r\n```",
